title: [ROCm] Share CUDA IsAllFinite kernel
body:
**Description**:
1.  Delete ROCm's IsAllFinite kernel, reuse the CUDA version (used via AMD Hipify).
2.  Add type inferencing for IsAllFinite's output (scalar bool), and update the shape to match in optimizer builder.
3.  IsAllFinite output doesn't need to explicitly be listed as CPU output - if onnxruntime decides the output needs to be used by CPU, then it will insert a MemcpyToHost node.  This also eliminates the need for a (1-byte) scratch buffer.

**Motivation and Context**
The goal is to reuse as much code as possible between CUDA and ROCm, as long as there's no performance or functional reason for diverging.  In this case, there's no measurable performance difference.

title: IOBindings in C++ API are missing a way to SynchronizeInputs.
body:
**Describe the bug**
When using IOBindings, input bindings that reside on host memory are not transferred to device memory when run is called.
This does not cause any error to be thrown or displayed, instead old values are silently used.

The root cause is this TODO: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/47185b951349fe49120f9be3b13d708490efc78f/onnxruntime/core/session/inference_session.cc#L1680

The user cannot call `IoBinding::SynchronizeInputs`, since that is hidden behind the API wall (user has to work with the `IoBinding` struct from onnxruntime_cxx_api.h.

As a workaround, the user has to call BindInput for the same memory location repeatedly for each inference run.
That causes per input:

- 1 std::string to be created when the `const char*` interface calls the `const std::string&` implementation
- 1 find operation over a `std::vector<std::string>`
- an additional allocation on the device for the new input values

**Urgency**
None.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution: Windows 10
- ONNX Runtime installed from: binary and source
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.5.2, 1.5.3, master, both cuda and dml
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): 2019
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): MSVC
- CUDA/cuDNN version: 10.2
- GPU model and memory: RTX2070Super

**To Reproduce**
- Setup a session using either CUDA or dml execution provider. Bind inputs and outputs through the C++ Api using host memory, and repeatedly call run while varying the input. Observe that output only depend on the input state before binding.

**Expected behavior**
Output takes input into account, by either synching automatically or offering a manual sync in the C++Api.

title: Implement missing pieces for ARM QLinearConv support
body:
**Description**: Implement the missing pieces to use the NHWC path for QLinearConv

**Motivation and Context**

title: Using a map of of ops to stages as input of partition function.
body:
### Description

This PR adds capability to explicitly define partition using a mapping of graph nodes to pipeline stages. See the PipelinePartition.DropoutGraph2stages for an example. 

In particular, we changed the “ApplyPipelinePartitionToMainGraph” code to use this mapping, we added a function “GetDeviceAssignmentMap” to convert the existing “cut_info” formulation to the new formulation (the partition definitions from before this PR should still work), and included new unit tests to compare the outputs of both partitions. 

As we want to avoid keeping two different partition functions, we moved the cut-based partition code to a partition_utils testing file.

### Motivation

The motivation for this work comes from the inability to partition certain graphs using the current partition API and algorithm. 
For example, we were not able to achieve the partitioning of the following graph:
```
graph(in):
      a = foo(in)     # Want to place on stage 0
      b = bar(a)    # Want to place on stage 1
      c = baz(b)   # Want to place on stage 2
      d = add(b, c)  # Want to place on stage 1
      e = mul(a, d)  # Want to place on stage 0
      e
```

We may want to achieve such partition _before_ AD to avoid copying large weights to a different device, for example. Note that this graph has similar shape to a training graph with pipeline parallelism and that we can easily extend the new partition algorithm to run _after_ AD, allowing for more flexible pipelines. This is the first PR towards more general pipeline parallelism.
